One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
Try a sentence.
We're testing.
One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
This is warm Friday, August 11, the year 2000, and I'm on the ninth floor of the Rudder Tower.
I have the delight of chatting with Jeanette Ferris about student years just a few years ago.
To introduce yourself to this process, Jeanette, talk about, describe family, growing up, where, when.
Tell us about yourself before you arrived in College Station.
In the 50s?
I'm a product of Breckenridge High School, Breckenridge, Texas, famous buckaroos, green and white, big football town.
My family consisted of my husband, Don, and two children, Donna K, and Randy, who were
Donald was born while we were at Texas A&M during 1956 through the years through 60.
My son was born after I departed from here in the year 1960.
And I was a student wife while my husband was pursuing a petroleum engineering degree.
But let's back up.
Your parents, where did they grow up?
My mother grew up in Oklahoma, my father grew up in Georgia, and met in Texas, and I spent my entire childhood in Breckenridge, Texas, living there, and my father was a rancher.
My mother kept the house, and she died when I was a teenager, and we did ranching and all the chores that ranching requires.
And you finished high school in what year?
1950, salutatorian of my class.
And then you got to College Station?
1956 with my husband when he arrived as a freshman at Texas A&M.
He spent a stint in the service and we worked in between times from graduation.
We married in 1952.
Why did you all come to A&M?
Why this place?

state school low tuition low rent open admissions and there was not there was not any particular aggie tradition in either family neither family and a good engineering petroleum engineering department and he was going to major in petroleum engineering because he knew a lot about the oil field he'd grown up with the oil field his parents were from the oil field did you all come to visit before you moved
Well, we came to visit knowing we wanted to move here.
We just came to look at it and see what the employment opportunities were for student lives on campus.
What did you, in that first visit, describe what you saw, what you found?
Well, I guess we knew that we wanted to come here, and we talked about job opportunities.
A lot of student wives worked on campus.
That truly was the staff on campus, and so there was a lot of turnover as students graduated or departed.
So opportunities for the wife to work and the husband to go to school and for the husband as a student to find part-time work was very high.
And it appeared that we had student housing on campus in what was called the old

student house college view college view there was a waiting list for college view so that we knew that we could not get in the first semester but we could probably find something off campus for the first semester all right now you came to visit about when to we can't think no to check things out we came in the summer before the fall of 1956. okay and then he enrolled did you have any contact any
We had some friends down here that they were in school.
He was working on a master's.
She was a student wife, and we had known her from my hometown.
He was not from my hometown, but we knew him.
But you all didn't know any faculty member or staff member, nobody to open the door for you?
No.
All right, then when you all moved, about what time of the year did you leave Breckenridge?
We came in either in August or early September of 56.
Usually classes didn't start until after Labor Day, so we probably moved here in August of 1956.
As much as you can recall, describe what belongings you brought with you.
Oh, that was easy.
We brought it in one small trailer pulling behind a 1956 Chevrolet Impala.
You had a new car?
We had a new car.
What was in the trailer?
Clothes, pots and pans, dishes, silverware.
No furniture?
No furniture.
No furniture.
And let's see, you had one little one?
No.
Oh, not yet.
She was born in 57.
Oh, okay.
And do you remember how much money y'all brought with you?
Well, we had a little money saved because my husband had been in service and I had been working the two years that he'd been in service.
So we had a little savings when we came.
And he had the GI Bill.
And he had the GI Bill, that's correct.
All right.
And do you remember when he applied for admission and when you heard a response?
When we came in the summer, I'm sure he applied and
We must have heard right away because I even interviewed for jobs while I was down here.
I interviewed at the registrar's office, the placement office, and one other office, which I can't remember.
Didn't hear from them, but we rented a post office box while we were here, so we'd have a mailing address.
The day we moved in with our trailer pulled behind that Chevrolet Impala.
We went to the post office, that was on a Friday.
I had a notice from the placement office that I was to report for work on Monday morning.
And needless to say, we scrambled for me to find a dress and some pantyhose so I could get to work on Monday morning, but we were elated.
You arrived what day, Friday?
On a Friday, or a Saturday, I can't remember which, but we went to the post office, we had a key.
Where did you find a place to live?
We're the Nations Bank's.
corner of Texas University.
What's the name of the bank today?
Oh, okay.
What's the name of the bank today?
I don't know.
It's changed names a few times.
There were some garage apartments located on that area of Texas Avenue and University where the bank sits today.
It was an upstairs apartment.
You parked your garage underneath, and the rent was very cheap.
Do you remember what it was?
Probably $50 a month, maybe.
Maybe $50 a month.
That's probably about what it was worth.
It had linoleum floors over the hardwood.
And then the corners, I remember that the linoleum was nailed down.

I couldn't figure out why when we moved in in September, but when winter came, I knew why because the wind whipped up and it just raised the linoleum up because the boards weren't completely together.
It was furnished, yes.
And so you reported for work where?
At the placement office for Mr. Wendell Horsley and Mr. Bill Hensel.
And do you remember what the pay was, the starting?
I don't know exactly, but I'm sure it was not more than $150 a month, but that seemed like a really good salary to us at that time.
Right, and then classes began about when?
probably the day after Labor Day at that time.

And as a freshman, it seemed like Don came in, went to the, and he was in the basic division, is what it was called then, instead of general studies, and he reported as a freshman a few days before the classes start for orientation, sort of.
Right, and what were your duties in that first task?

I was working with graduating seniors preparing their credentials for interviewing, and so I had to sit down with them, write their resumes, and put it in a format that would present their credentials so that when the companies came to see what graduates fit with their interview schedules, we had them all in file, make sure their transcripts were in there and their letters of reference or reference forms.
I could use either one.
Share, if you can, share some recollections of some
plus and minus experience with those resume developments.
There had to be some goofy things that students did or didn't do.
Well, we tried to set up a standard format to try to force them to answer certain questions.
And of course, I guess in some ways there was always that feeling that they were padding their resume.
But most of them were really sincere.
They'd bring in documentation that indicated they were a member of
tall beta pi or some of the academic societies our engineers council we knew most of the a lot of the students on campus there was only about
7,000, 8,000 students on campus at that time, so it was not hard to read the newspaper and know a lot about the students.
In the fall, you had about 8,000 students.
In the spring, you usually had about 7,000.
And then in the summer, you only had, if you had 2,000 enrollment, that was a high number.
So we knew a lot about them.
We could verify their grade point ratio.
We could verify their grade point ratio in their major because we could take their transcript and actually figure that out.
So it was not too hard.
Our goal, the placement office at that time wanted a one page resume.
So there wasn't a lot of room for us to put a lot of verbiage in there.
Do you remember any goofy efforts by any student to kind of fudge a little and maybe increase their resume more than factually it deserved?
It's been too long, Haskell.
I can't remember those.
And you reported to whom?
I reported directly to Bill Hensel, and he reported to Wendell Horsley.
And what were the normal working hours?
8 to 5 during the week, but during a lot of the placement time, we had to work on Sunday because the office was also responsible for continuing education activities that came in.
So a lot of the conferences started on Sunday.
So, excuse me, many times we had to work on Sunday for a registration for continuing education activities.
And you all were located where physically?
What building?
We were in a wooden building.
that has long ago been destroyed, of course.
And I can't remember where it was located on campus.
I just don't remember where it was located.
But it was an old wooden building.
And this was under the reported to Mr. Heaton, I presume.
I do not know.
I don't know who the placement office reported to at that time.
Alright, describe this freshman getting in the routine of studying and classes and so forth.
Well, he found out very quickly that he didn't have enough background to really be a successful petroleum engineer.
So he went to A&M Consolidated and bought some of the calculus and algebra books and studied on his own so that he could begin his studies for petroleum engineering.
He studied that at the same time as taking his courses.
And they took anywhere from usually about 18 hours per semester.
But I've seen his transcript in many semesters.
Don took as many as 21 hours a semester and he graduated

about fifth or sixth in his class in petroleum engineering when he graduated in four years i was going to say and when you all arrived you assumed it was that the undergraduate years were going to be four years but at the same time since don had some oil field experience he didn't have to do a summer internship so and my job required that i worked 12 months out of the year so he took the college catalog and figured that he could get

a business degree at the same time he was getting his petroleum engineering degree by going summers and the long terms and so when he graduated in four years he actually graduated with two degrees one in business administration and one in petroleum engineering and still graduated with very good grades all right and as you all are getting started where did you first begin to make some friends and who were they
Well, you made friends with the people that he was in class with because he began to know a lot of them.
Robert Lacey became a very, very close friend of my husband's and probably was his best friend until the day my husband died.
What was Lacey doing there?
He was a student.
He and Don were both students.
They started together and graduated together.
And Mr. Lacy started out in petroleum engineering, but his second year, he changed to math and graduated in math.
But for the first two years, they took a lot of courses together.
Even in the summer, they took calculus and trig and calculus and geometry and some of those courses together.
Other friends.
I became friends with people I worked with at the placement office because their husbands were also in school.
One was Daisy Smithwick and her husband was Dick Smithwick, who was playing football here at that time under Bear Bryant, and he had been one of those that went to West Texas at
Junction.
Junction.
And was headed for vet school.
And his senior year, he realized that he couldn't play football and be a veterinarian.
He couldn't keep up his grades, so he chose to be a veterinarian and dropped out his senior year.
We became fast friends, and we're still friends today, and that's a 44.
That's a 44-year friendship, I guess.
That's right.
So it's mine with Mr. Lacy at the same time.
And then we became friends with a lot of the students and their wives that Don studied with.
There was lots of study sessions.
Most of them who were in petroleum engineering spent a lot of time in the Petty Lab.
So we were left by, the wives were left by ourselves a lot, and we became fast friends.
In that first fall,
What was it like to go to Aggie football games for you as a new arrival?
Well, it was exciting.

I can remember one of the worst storms we had was we were playing TCU and a storm came in and the light poles bent completely over and we didn't realize how dangerous it was as we sat there on that stadium and played.
That was our entertainment.
we really didn't have a lot of money for entertainment, so the football games were about our only entertainment.

We went to Town Hall occasionally, which was held in Gine Hall at that time, and of course Gine Hall is no longer on campus either, but that was about the extent of our entertainment, maybe a once a month movie.
Alright, with his tough academic load and your job, normally you left home what time in the morning?
During long semesters, we would leave home about 7.30.
My job was at 8 and classes were at 8.
However, in the summertime, classes started at 7 because there were no air-conditioned buildings.
And so the classes started at 7 and I would go to work when he came to campus because we only had one car.
And then with his student jobs, we delivered the paper in the summer to...
the student apartments, and so we'd get up at four and deliver papers.
Which paper?
The Eagle, I think.
The Eagle?
Yes, the Eagle.
I'm not sure it was called Eagle at that time.
I think it had a longer name, but we'd deliver the Eagle or the Houston Post.
Maybe it was the Houston Post.
I guess it was the Houston Post.
And then we'd go home and shower.
Do you remember what y'all made for the paper job?
Oh, probably if we made $100 a month, we felt good about it.
We needed the $100, so we did that.
All right, now, did he have the GI Bill?
He did have the GI Bill.
Student paper.
Student paper.
Your full-time job.
And then he served as apartment manager for a few of the complexes over in the student housing.
Okay.
But you lived that whole first year in the garage apartment?
No, we lived only, we got to move during the spring semester to College View.
Oh.
I don't remember, we didn't get to move the very first part of the year.
Sometime during the term, somebody moved out and we were on the list.
So our number was up and we moved there and we moved
sometime in the late spring of 57.
Describe as much as you can a College View apartment.

Well one thing about it if you serve soup you had to make sure that you didn't fill the bowl full because it wasn't level and so the soup would spill out so you the floors weren't very level they were two bedroom un-air-conditioned bunk beds in one room not even a full bed in the other room but I'd call a three-quarter bed
a bus couch, a rocking chair, a little wooden table, very, very tiny kitchen, very small shower bath, no tub, and the closets had no doors on them.
They were just stalls for closets.
Washing machine?
No, no washing machine, no dryer.
But there was a refrigerator.
There was a refrigerator, and there was a plug for a washing machine.
So that was our big purchase during the spring of 57 was to purchase a washing machine.
What about a dryer?
We never owned a dryer while we lived there.
So you used a solar dryer?
Used a solar dryer, hung them on the clotheslines.

And matter of fact, one of the incidents that my husband had to resolve was a fight between two women using the clothesline because you were assigned a certain line to hang your laundry on because there were eight apartments

in each building and so you took your line and no more when your clothes dried you could hang additional clothes so it was it was an interesting concept lots of interesting conversations took place at the clothesline uh about what what were what were student wives concerned about in those days survival and child care
A lot of the married people did have children.
We had our first child November of 57 when Don was a sophomore here.
And there were no daycare centers.
There was no university daycare center and very few commercial ones in town.
So you had to find an individual who was willing to keep your child.
There were one or two of the women in the barracks who would take care of other children, but those were few and far between.
All right, as this child is on the way, you worked until about...
I worked on Thursday.
She was born on Saturday.
Okay.
There was no maternity leave.
Maternity leave did not exist at Texas A&M at that time.
And your doctor, do you remember who the... Dr. Gephardt was my doctor.
At old St. Joseph's?
At old St. Joseph's Hospital, that's correct.
And then I was off work for five weeks.
And then I started working and you had to terminate because your job was not held for you since there was no maternity leave.
And then when she was five weeks old, I started working in the dean's office in the College of Engineering working on their ECPD accreditation.
They had someone working on it in the daytime, so I would take her car bed up at night and work on the reports, and my husband would study while I worked.
And then on weekends I would work, either Don Keper or Mr. Charlie Crawford's wife actually took care of my little baby.
He was the associate dean of engineering.
And how many hours a week were you working at that point?
Oh, probably 20, 30 hours a week, and then I hadn't been there about six or seven weeks, and they offered me a full-time job, and so I went to work full-time for them.
about January of 1958.
You don't remember what the pay was, any of those?
Well, probably $200 a month at a max.
And then I worked there until my husband graduated in May of 1960.
And in the 60s, I was pregnant again.
And the maternity leave policy at Texas A&M at that time was you had to terminate at six months.
That was a requirement.
You had to bring a note or letter from your doctor that said you were six months pregnant and you had to terminate.

So my husband graduated on about the 15th of May and I think I was six months pregnant the 15th of May and so I managed to work till he graduated and a paycheck came in in June from Arco, the company he chose to go to work for.
Alright, let's go back to those student years.
What courses do you remember for him
were important because of who was teaching it or what he learned?
What were the, what seemed to be the meaningful?
Well, of course, his main interests were the petroleum engineering courses, and they were the hardest.
Who were some of the special teachers?
Dr. Bass.
Bass?
Dr. Bass.
Dr. Russell over in geology, you took a lot of geology courses.
Calhoun was not... Calhoun, he was not one of Don's teachers.
If he was here, he was not teaching.
He didn't take any courses under him.
Who did your husband go to for advice and counsel?
There wasn't a lot of advice and counsel.

After you got to be a junior or senior, usually your major professors, you could go to them and ask for advice, but most of the time you were pretty much on your own and maybe one or two in business because he went over to work out a degree plan for business while he was here doing that.
But Charlie Randall wasn't yet associate dean.
No, Charlie Ransdell was still in the basic division, and no, he was not an associate.
Who headed petroleum then, do you remember?
Who the senior person was, the key person?
Who's the building named for?
I want to say Hal Booty.
I can't remember who was head of the department.
I just don't remember that at this time.
When you went to work in engineering, let's shift to that,

uh where was the dean's office it was in francis hall uh second floor francis hall and the dean was well when i went to work fred benson was the dean and mr harrington we had just well we did a lot of work for mr harrington had he just left the dean ship or had he left the vice president's position i think vice president vice president position but we did a lot of work for mr harrington i'm not sure why but we did
describe Fred Benson as the dean?
Oh, Fred Benson was always a gentleman, always a gentleman.
Very stoic, very quiet man, but very effective.
During the time that I worked for him, a handsome man.
He could have doubled for Clark Gable, and as a matter of fact, I remarked about that once, and someone said, well, they weren't sure they saw that resemblance, and one day I

got an article that was sent in the mail to him and at the top of it it had written across Gabriel Benson but he yes he was a wonderful dean and only concerned about the students and the academic life at Texas A&M served on the facilities committee he was a civil engineer and he was also head of TTI at that time and so that was a joint venture and his remark I remember him saying I will never sign
another building be built on this campus that's not air conditioned and air conditioning did start with a few buildings in the early 60s.
You said that he was a you talked about his qualities give some examples of his thoughtfulness to the staff.
When my daughter was about six months old I had to have major surgery on an emergency basis and
Since my parents were deceased and Don's parents lived in New York, I didn't really have anybody to take care of the child while I was in the hospital and my husband was in school.
And unbeknownst to me, Fred Vinson went home and asked his wife, Marge, and his youngest child's name was Clark.
He said, Marge, do you think we could
take Clark's baby bed out of the attic and take care of that baby for Jeanette.
I found that out much later and didn't know it at the time.
Of course I made arrangements for someone to keep my daughter, but I didn't know he'd even consider such.
And of course Margie's answer was yes, they would take care of that baby.
Now I've also heard that he had certain guidelines as to what things were to be done and not to be done.
give some examples of the guidelines in the office, things he did not put up with.
He didn't put up with, I guess I shouldn't say he didn't put up with, but he certainly objected to anyone who wasn't true to their marriage and stepped outside those lines if a department head were a

not being as faithful to his wife as he thought he should, or there were rumors floating, he'd call that person in, and if he thought that any student had been mistreated, he'd call the department head in.
He was always very, he was very supportive of his department heads, but at the same time, he was also very concerned about his students.
And how did he treat the staff, the office staff?
With great respect.
I never saw him chew anyone in the office out, ever.
What did you realize early on were the, for you as a member of the staff, were the guidelines though?
I worked with J.G.
McGuire a lot who worked on the co-op program and worked with all the students who were on probation.
So we saw a lot of problem students and Mr. Benson expected us to handle our job unless the situation got very hot so to speak and
If I did my job and did a good job, I was rewarded for it.
I was always there for a merit increase if there were any merit increases to be done.
And also he trusted those unless he had a reason not to.
So I never, if you didn't break that trust, it was there.
What did a young woman, her physical appearance, how did a young woman
prepare herself in what she wore and her hair and her makeup and so forth in those days?
Well, we wore dresses.
There were no pants on campus at that time.
We all wore dresses.
They were certainly below the knees.
We wore hose, even though the building was not air-conditioned.
We were expected to wear hose.
And I can remember how miserable it was to be in hose and a dress and no air conditioning.
There were a few fans on the floor to try to keep us cool, but that was not very effective.
And we didn't have a lot of clothes, but you didn't have to have a variety.
We didn't wear suits, just dresses.
Did people drink coffee at their desk in those days?
Yes, but you also got a coffee break.
You got about a 15-minute break, and if you had a large staff, they would divide it up.
Some go in the coffee room at one time, sometimes others.
always somebody on the telephones in the front door, so to speak.
And usually Mr. Benson would join us in the coffee room and be very relaxed and visit with the staff.
That's how I got to know them.
What about smoking?
There was no smoking in the office.
It might have been allowed, but no one smoked.
So we never thought about smoking.
None of the women in the office smoked, as far as you knew?
No.
Did some of the men, some of the deans, did they
No, not in the 50s.
I don't remember any of them who smoked.
Mr. Crawford didn't, of course, and Mr. Benson didn't, and Mr. McGuire, and Dr. Winerdi didn't.
So, no, I don't remember any of them smoking in the office.
Right.
Describe the staff.
When you began, describe the professional staff, Benson and who were the other professionals in the office.
Dr. Charles Crawford, who had been...
at one time, I believe, head of the mechanical engineering department, was the associate dean.
Dr. Richard Winerdi was hired while I was actually there.
He was the youngest full professor on this campus that was hired from 58 to 60.
His major was also petroleum engineering.
With Crawford, what was his duty?
He was in charge of reporting, accreditation, the professional side of the house.
Mr. Benson always chaired his department head's council.
Mr. Crawford sat in, but Mr. Benson was always there to handle that.
So policy issues usually came from the dean.
Mr. Crawford might make some recommendations to him, but usually the policy issues were decided by Mr. Benson and the department heads.
All right.
This young man, Winerdi, make believe I didn't know him.
Describe him in that era.
He was a very dynamic figure, extremely intelligent.
I'm sure genius intelligence came on.
